Satanta Grade School
March 24 at 1:42 AM ·

Good evening parents,

On Wednesday from 3:00 to 6:00 your student’s school materials and technology devices will be available for pick up. GS pick up will be spread out around the GS building. JH and HS pick up will be outside the concession stand doors of the HS. This will be a drive up pick up. We ask that you and your children remain in your vehicle. Teachers will come to you in your vehicle. The technology devices will require a parent/guardian signature to be released. They can not be released other than to a parent/guardian. If you know you do not want your child's school devices to go home with you, please email the principal at hstegman@usd507.org to request they be taken out of your child's bag.

We also ask that if your child has library books, school uniforms, or other school materials that you bring them. Teachers will be able to take those.

We appreciate your continued support and patience.
Heather Stegman
USD 507 Principal

post_text: Seniors...the news and guidelines for schools and states change by the hour it seems! During these crazy, uncharted waters ...please know you are loved and we can’t wait to see how you tackle your futures! Right now, our district has made the decision to stay out of school one more week. We do not know what will happen this week and what guidance we will be given by the state. We don’t know what it means for events and special times we have planned for the rest of the semester. However, this is a great article that expresses how we can for sure handle whatever obstacles we might face! It is written by a teacher in LA, but has pertinent advice for seniors living anywhere! Please take the time to read this, be encouraged, and remain hopeful! Stay safe and be sure to reach out via text or email if you need anything from me! ❤️Mrs. Anthony
shared_text:
DEUTSCH29.WORDPRESS.COM
La. Teacher of the Year: An Open Letter to High School Seniors During Coronavirus Crisis
text:
Seniors...the news and guidelines for schools and states change by the hour it seems! During these crazy, uncharted waters ...please know you are loved and we can’t wait to see how you tackle your futures! Right now, our district has made the decision to stay out of school one more week. We do not know what will happen this week and what guidance we will be given by the state. We don’t know what it means for events and special times we have planned for the rest of the semester. However, this is a great article that expresses how we can for sure handle whatever obstacles we might face! It is written by a teacher in LA, but has pertinent advice for seniors living anywhere! Please take the time to read this, be encouraged, and remain hopeful! Stay safe and be sure to reach out via text or email if you need anything from me! ❤️Mrs. Anthony

DODGEGLOBE.COM
Eastern Star to offer scholarship

Dodge Globe
February 17 at 6:46 PM ·

St. Bernard No. 97 Order of Eastern Star in Dodge City, will offer a southwest Kansas student enrolling for the first time in a post-secondary institution a $250 scholarship.

According to St. Bernard No. 97 Order of Eastern Star, students with Masonic affiliation will have first consideration, as well as students who know a Mason or Eastern Star member.

The scholarship is open to students in Ford, Comanche, Kiowa, Edwards, Hodgeman, Clark, Meade, Gray, Finney, Haskell, Seward, Stevens, Grant, Kearney, Morton, Stanton, Hamilton, Pawnee, Rush, Wichita, Ness, Lane, Scott and Greeley counties.

post_text: We hope everyone’s Christmas break is off to a relaxing, great start! Due to some technical errors, the grade reports you will receive for your students in high school in the next few days will have some errors and omissions. One error is they are titled...”Spring Progress Reports’!!! We clearly know it is not Spring yet! Next, if your child took any concurrent classes, meaning a class for dual credit to the high school and for college credit, they did not print their scores on the reports. We apologize for these errors. However, if you log on to your Power School accounts, you can see the classes with the grades. If you would like a new, accurate report printed for you, or if you need help accessing your Power School records, please call the high school office after break and we will accommodate your requests! Again, we apologize for the errors and will do all in our power to alleviate this from happening in the future! Have a great break with your families!

Satanta High School
October 19, 2019 at 6:45 AM ·

Have you signed on to the One TRIBE Pledge?

I believe . . .

that creating a school community that is a safe and welcoming environment for all students, teachers, and staff begins with me.

that everyone has the right to attend a school where they feel included, valued, and respected.

that it is my responsibility to protect the members of my school community by standing up against bullying, harassment, and exclusion.

that I must challenge and report incidents of discriminating behavior, working together to demonstrate that hate will not be tolerated here.

that my school is worth fighting for and is a place where I can find people who support me in the same way I support them. Because of this, I will do more than “just show up.” Instead, I will work continuously to improve our school, our community, and myself.

that I am a member of the TRIBE.

I will honor this commitment in my classes, in my personal life, and in all my pursuits both on and off school grounds. I pledge to make everyone in our school feel safe, valued, and a part of our TRIBE.

Satanta High School
August 5, 2019 at 4:52 AM ·

Going back to school can be expensive! This year the newly formed SPEAR Project (Students Providing Educational and Athletic Resources) hopes to move beyond the USD 507 Care Closet’s efforts to provide food and personal hygiene assistance to students in need by helping to ensure that all students have the things they need to be successful. If you’re in need of a little extra help (maybe with football cleats or volleyball kneepads or three-ring binders) simply fill out a form (https://docs.google.com/document/d/13z_mCE7Jk4aCHijbwFxi-Lp3ZzbODgTh_D5N69QVif0/edit?usp=sharing) and return it to Christy in the high school office. This service is currently focusing on students in grades 6-12.

Please note that while SPEAR is associated with the FCCLA Care Closets project, it is not meant to replace it any way. Nutritional and personal hygiene items will still be available for both high school and grade school students.

If you would like to donate toward either the SPEAR or Care Closets projects, checks can be made out to Satanta High School with FCCLA Care Closets in the memo line.

Satanta Grade School
July 16, 2019 at 4:53 PM ·

The Kansas Department of Health and Environment has released new requirements and recommendations for student immunizations beginning for the 2019-2020 school year.

The changes impact students entering Kindergarten, 1st, 7th & 11th grades for the 19-20 school year-
Hepatitis A: Two doses required for all students entering Kindergarten and 1st grade.
Meningococcal: One dose required for students entering 7th (ages 11-12) grade and another dose required for students entering 11th grade (ages 16-18).

You may receive these vaccines at your physician's office or the Haskell County Health Department.

Proof of these vaccines must be received in the the nurse's office.

If parents have questions or concerns regarding their child's immunization status, please speak with the school nurse, Haskell County Health Department, or your healthcare provider.
text:
Satanta Grade School
July 16, 2019 at 4:53 PM ·

The Kansas Department of Health and Environment has released new requirements and recommendations for student immunizations beginning for the 2019-2020 school year.

The changes impact students entering Kindergarten, 1st, 7th & 11th grades for the 19-20 school year-
Hepatitis A: Two doses required for all students entering Kindergarten and 1st grade.
Meningococcal: One dose required for students entering 7th (ages 11-12) grade and another dose required for students entering 11th grade (ages 16-18).

You may receive these vaccines at your physician's office or the Haskell County Health Department.

Proof of these vaccines must be received in the the nurse's office.

If parents have questions or concerns regarding their child's immunization status, please speak with the school nurse, Haskell County Health Department, or your healthcare provider.

post_text: Every single person experiences the process of grief in their own unique way. Don’t let anyone tell you how it should feel or go for you. There is no set order or timeline that one goes through each stage. The most important thing is that you use supports around you. Surround yourself with family and friends and utilize counseling and therapy services if needed.

Crystal Thacker Taylor‎180 Student Ministries
June 20, 2018 at 1:43 AM ·

The youth in this community have suffered a tremendous loss today and we want you to know that we are here and we care. Tomorrow night we will open the FBC Activity Building from 7:00 – 9:00 P.M. for anyone needing to talk, share memories, cry, ask questions, pray, hangout, get a hug, just sit and ponder, whatever it is you need. Grief looks different for everyone and this is a safe zone with no judgement; a place where you are welcome to come and do just that…grieve. In our thoughts and prayers always, The 180 Student Ministry Staff.

Satanta High School
May 3, 2018 at 2:22 PM ·

The Satanta High School graduation ceremony will take place on Sunday, May 13, 2018, at 3:00 p.m. in the Satanta High School gymnasium. Please keep in mind that if you are not in the gym before 3:00 p.m, you will be asked to remain outside in the concessions area for the duration of the ceremony. This will keep the noise level down during the ceremony and allow the students, parents, friends, and faculty gathered there to enjoy this momentous occasion.

The Satanta High School Class of 2018 includes the following students: Kaden Anthony, Ty Blair, RaeAnne Blevins, Alondra Botello, Nidia Caro, Noel Caro, Maria Contreras, Willy Garcia, Morgan Hoskinson, Alex Howie, Cassidy Jones, Javier Ledezma, Betty Loewen, Kolton Maturey, Alexis Mayorga, Javier Morales, Oscar Moreno, Clarissa Najera, Carley Oxford, Miles Purcell, Alex Rios, and Lorenzo Salazar.

Howie and Najera have been named valedictorian and salutatorian, respectively, and will both speak. Mr. Tim Dusin will be the guest speaker. The Class of 2018 is sponsored by Ms. Janie Lutz and Mrs. Courtney Dunn.
